commit_message:
Adds test for list/get volume attachments V2 APIs

This patch adds the test for following Nova V2 APIs-
- List volume attachments
- Get volume attachment
Response Schema has been added for the same.

To make consistent in server_client and easy for tests to compare
the response, this Patch also change the returned response body from
server_client's attach_volume().

Note- XML test cases is not implemented as it is deprecated.
New test cases has been skipped for XML.

Change-Id: Iee055ceaad135bba4a57b010d1e08652e2d13598

commit_message:
Pool Manager - Pool Manager Proxy Backend and Devstack

- Incorporated pool manager into Devstack
- Changed pool_name to pool_id in [service:pool_manager]

    ENABLED_SERVICES+=,designate-pool-manager
    DESIGNATE_BACKEND_DRIVER=bind9_pool

Partially-implements: blueprint server-pools-service

reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 6926, 'name': 'Bogdan Dobrelya', 'email': 'bdobreli@redhat.com', 'username': 'bogdando'}, {'_account_id': 7468, 'name': 'Sergey Vasilenko', 'email': 'svasilenko@mirantis.com', 'username': 'xenolog'}, {'_account_id': 8971, 'name': 'Fuel CI', 'username': 'fuel-ci', 'inactive': True, 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 9037, 'name': 'Dmitry Ilyin', 'email': 'idv1985@gmail.com', 'username': 'dilyin'}, {'_account_id': 9387, 'name': 'Aleksandr Didenko', 'email': 'adidenko@mirantis.com', 'username': 'AD'}]
revisions:
[{'number': 5, 'created': '2014-11-12 12:30:17.000000000', 'files': ['deployment/puppet/openstack/manifests/corosync.pp', 'deployment/puppet/pacemaker_wrappers/manifests/service.pp', 'deployment/puppet/osnailyfacter/manifests/cluster_ha.pp'], 'message': 'Fix missing openstack::corosync dependency for HA services

W/o this fix, pacemaker and corosync could be installed too
late causing pcs resource start operation timed out.
Also, ::corosync class could install pacemaker and corosync
packages out of openstack::corosync class evaluation, but we
want these packages installed while openstack::corosync is being
evaluated as well.

The solution is:
* ensure all pcs provided services will be
  evaluated after openstack::corosync class.
* add missing anchor dependency for ::corosync class call
  in openstack::corosync

Related-bug: #1390745

Change-Id: Icea3cdbb857a742cc35705f4de3b2cfba1847d1c
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Fix missing openstack::corosync dependency for HA services

W/o this fix, pacemaker and corosync could be installed too
late causing pcs resource start operation timed out.
Also, ::corosync class could install pacemaker and corosync
packages out of openstack::corosync class evaluation, but we
want these packages installed while openstack::corosync is being
evaluated as well.

The solution is:
* ensure all pcs provided services will be
  evaluated after openstack::corosync class.
* add missing anchor dependency for ::corosync class call
  in openstack::corosync

Related-bug: #1390745

Change-Id: Icea3cdbb857a742cc35705f4de3b2cfba1847d1c
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Add a new field type 'relation' to objects

This adds support for a new field type called "relation" to a field
allowing a field to be a relation, meaning you can have for example a Domain
with a relation to a RecordList.

Trying to access a relation that is not set with raise a exception
ReloationNotLoaded.

We add a recordsets relationsip on Domain so we can pass around a Domain object
with the recordsets attached.

Change-Id: Ic45313df5316e6af1a7424b6f6a11bebf6fdb3ad

commit_message:
Squashed two patches that simultaneously block the gate

===

Redis: for non-strict Redis class, expired ttl is None, not -1

Python bindings for Redis return None if ttl is expired instead of -1
when Redis class is used (instead of StrictRedis) which is the default
for oslo-incubator. Fixed unit test to pass the check.

The patch does not belong to master where old RPC layer was removed
since Kilo. Neither it belongs to oslo.messaging since the test was not
copied there.

Closes-Bug: #1259532
Change-Id: Id54e78ca56bb5a5bf1cdad31bc5965ff02c0d9b4

===

Fix build break - switch from str to hash for lookup

Closes-Bug: #1372177
Change-Id: I1a1f70bb204d3f43bdacd4ded53225f8416f1639
(cherry picked from commit 6b65a41dd2653aa9e2558c510fa9d3ca3538a908)

commit_message:
Increased keystone token expiration time to 24h

Long lived token will allow to use it in OSTF tests and in
long running upgrade where 1h token might not be sufficient.
Such token will also improve user experience when we switch
to storing token instead of storing user credentials.

Change-Id: I81ba5c11034fca8a332ec2e92f1f9804523e14f6
Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments
(cherry picked from commit 62644311e19ca569e9b6cd3dcaf0cac479e0f7ed)

commit_message:
javelin: add network and secgroup resources

This patch aims to bring Neutron support in tempest/javelin by:
- create networks
- create subnets in the networks
- create routers
- connect routers to networks
- Create security groups and rules
- Assign a security group after server creation
- Check security groups survive after upgrade

Partial-bug #1330178
Change-Id: I2f54aec71e452361f9741b4ccb5d5bb6f358abf9
Co-Authored-By: Jakub Libosvar <libosvar@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Using flavor id to retrieve  extra spec in scheduler

Because table instance_type_extra_specs store instance type info
mapping by instance type id instead of uuid, we need to use flavor
id to retrieve instance extra spec.

Change-Id: I6398ebd64878f0b53b21f73463a3fd2050fdfac3
Closes-Bug: 1390075

commit_message:
Remove usage of admin_token

* Added new tenant/project: services
* Added two new users with admin roles to 'services' project:
  ostf and nailgun
* Use generated passwords for ostf and nailgun keystone users and
  remove admin_token
* OSTF and nailgun will use their users to validate keystone tokens
  instead of admin_token
* Added new services and endpoints for keystone, ostf, nailgun. Now
  it's possible to use keystone service catalog to discover their URLs

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint access-control-master-node-improvments
Depends: Ibe3844da784656f02673c32c2f98cb67bbdb3e89

Change-Id: I9860257b1b392be31de8ff9e09b95e9a3c6ba3f7
(cherry picked from commit 9dae245d0d91203f1c6acf24ae9ba4eb18b98295)

commit_message:
Parallel test execution with py.test

Patch adds ability to execute test run distributed over
several processes, each one with isolated database.

Assumptions:
- nailgun user, requires createdb permission, if not please precreate
  databases in format described below
- postgres database will be used for initial connection
- for environment where createdb can not be granted, like ci
  operator need to create several databases, nailgun[0-7],
  count of databases should be equal to TEST_WORKERS variable
- If no TEST_WORKERS provided - default database name will be used,
  it is almost every time nailgun, but you can overwrite it with
  TEST_NAILGUN_DB env variable

To execute tests on your local environment:
  py.test -n 4 nailgun/tests/

DocImpact
Partial-Bug: 1388751
Change-Id: I6037108f1888b61f971a10db5209b20712467173

commit_message:
Fix output of unmet dependences, add support for 'udeb' packages.

- When debian package manager selected to install older version
  of a package, but newer version requested by other package,
  then output with error is slightly different then was expected:
  Depends: package-name (= v2.0) but (v1.0) is to be installed

- Add support for 'udeb' packages for debian-installer.
  Now *.udeb packages can be placed to the folder
  /var/www/nailgun/ubuntu/x86_64/pool/debian-installer , repository
  can be updated with the sctipt 'regenerate_ubuntu_repo' with the
  same way as for *.deb packages.
  Also 'package_testing_deb' now can be used for testing gerrit
  reviews that contain any of *.deb or *.udeb packages.

Change-Id: Ib11546f7aa75e23e7f879170416c7183ff519df7
Closes-Bug: #1391569

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2014-10-30 17:27:47.000000000', 'files': ['elements/redhat-common/pre-install.d/02-lsb'], 'message': 'Only copy lsb_release file if it exists

The existing check for -z "$NO_SOURCE_REPOSITORIES" is insufficient
since this variable may be unset for a variety of reasons.

This patch updates 02-lsb so that it just simply checks for the
file that it installs within the script. If no file exists it
is assumed that a packaged version should be installed instead.

The motivation for this fix is to resolve an issue I hit
when using the new --install-type=package DIB option. When
using this option source repositories is skipped unless
it is explicitly enabled for a specific package...
thus causing lsb_release not to exist. I did not have the
corresponding NO_SOURCE_REPOSITORIES env variable set...
nor do I think that one should have to set such a variable
to use this option.

Change-Id: I28fdac4307902342711f2f30d408e8d6c18ee4ab
'}]
commit_message:
Only copy lsb_release file if it exists

The existing check for -z "$NO_SOURCE_REPOSITORIES" is insufficient
since this variable may be unset for a variety of reasons.

This patch updates 02-lsb so that it just simply checks for the
file that it installs within the script. If no file exists it
is assumed that a packaged version should be installed instead.

The motivation for this fix is to resolve an issue I hit
when using the new --install-type=package DIB option. When
using this option source repositories is skipped unless
it is explicitly enabled for a specific package...
thus causing lsb_release not to exist. I did not have the
corresponding NO_SOURCE_REPOSITORIES env variable set...
nor do I think that one should have to set such a variable
to use this option.

Change-Id: I28fdac4307902342711f2f30d408e8d6c18ee4ab

subject: cliutils restore python3 string decode
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2014-11-10 12:36:27.000000000', 'files': ['openstack/common/cliutils.py', 'tests/unit/test_cliutils.py'], 'message': "cliutils restore python3 string decode

Since the the safe_encode function moved from incubator strutils
to oslo.utils the print_list and print_dict functions don't work
as expected on python3, because the safe_encode in encodeutils
lacks the logic to decode on python3 like existed in strutils.

So, reinstate that logic within the print_list and print_dict
functions, and add a couple of simple tests to ensure we keep
them working (no other tests check the string output from the
prints AFAICS).

Change-Id: I42f6aa802c1f94fcbf0e9170024cf37089f92782
Closes-Bug: #1390505
"}]
commit_message:
cliutils restore python3 string decode

Since the the safe_encode function moved from incubator strutils
to oslo.utils the print_list and print_dict functions don't work
as expected on python3, because the safe_encode in encodeutils
lacks the logic to decode on python3 like existed in strutils.

So, reinstate that logic within the print_list and print_dict
functions, and add a couple of simple tests to ensure we keep
them working (no other tests check the string output from the
prints AFAICS).

Change-Id: I42f6aa802c1f94fcbf0e9170024cf37089f92782
Closes-Bug: #1390505

commit_message:
Correctly catch InstanceExists in servers create API

When osapi_compute_unique_server_name_scope is set to project
or global an attempt to create a server with a name which
already exists results in an InstanceExists exception being raised.
This was not being handled in the API layer causing a 500
status error code. This patch fixes it so the exception is caught
correctly and a 409 Conflict is returned instead

Closes-Bug: 1376936
Closes-Bug: 1377176
(cherry picked from commit Ifee3476622b227991a4c2a2780ae7ff23787ccb9)

Change-Id: If20bbc2caf577143f410e3a3abb17726f685f35a

commit_message:
Isolate sudo syslog logs locally

W/o this fix sudo messages from Openstack root-wrappers are *too*
numerous and just flooding the network around and consume additional
space at the remote log server.

The solution is do not send sudo logs remotely, but store them locally
instead.
* Add new /var/log/sudo.log file for sudo logs at Openstack nodes
* Add /var/log/sudo.log to rotation plans as well.

DocImpact
Closes-bug: #1390376

Change-Id: Ife1cb9d6c342966d09329745c8dfeb96e15737be
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Fix fuel_6_0.py migration script

We have wrong approach of writing alembic migration scripts -
we have all-in-one migration file, which is wrong, because Alembic
itself promotes to use a separate file for separate migration task.

The issue shows us that we can't and shouldn't separate schema and data
migration, since they are a whole thing and rely on each other.

Change-Id: Ic1c5c69243211ae9b48088b6a4787a47ce6e5515
Closes-Bug: #1391525

commit_message:
fix network discovery meters

currently we let neutronclient authenticate against keystone. this
makes it impossible for us to figure out whether service is valid
until too late (when we call poll neutronclient).

this patch adds keystoneclient to check_keystone decorator so it
can verify endpoints when keystoneclient is not available.

Closes-Bug: #1361818
Change-Id: Ia374e9b422ed8fa088b28ecf200161248136b09e

commit_message:
Show "0" in UI if there is no real cores

Currently, if we have some node without real cores we will see next
string in UI:

    CPU: ? (1)

Since now, we will see "0" instead of "?"

    CPU: 0 (1)

Change-Id: I4d3dfad5f2a96b2d303797ff8e2dd594ad78b19c
Closes-Bug: #1382545

commit_message:
adding local boot support for uboot arm arch

Once pxe image is booted. The boot.scr file should be
able to boot from local file system. kernel and ramdisk
address are provided by environment variables set on
arm board.

Change-Id: I4ad523f85baf488e50a9bc64a926830d4d749195

subject: Properly parse the keypair response and workaround issues
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2014-11-01 20:12:48.000000000', 'files': ['openstack/tests/compute/v2/test_keypairs.py', 'openstack/compute/v2/keypairs.py'], 'message': 'Properly parse the keypair response and workaround issues

The API for keypairs has some anomolies that need to be worked
around:
* When you get a list of keypairs, the response is
  {"keypairs": ["keypair": {data} with an extra "keypair".
  This was a little hard to notice when functionally testing this
  earlier because when you print it out, it looks correct until
  you notice everything is in the "keypair" attribute.
* Filtering on find is broken and so a find method was added to
  manually do the filtering.
* Create needs to populate the private key in the response
  resource object.

Change-Id: Ic2fffc5a48e4270acd2711e7762cc3157a7a71df
'}]
commit_message:
Properly parse the keypair response and workaround issues

The API for keypairs has some anomolies that need to be worked
around:
* When you get a list of keypairs, the response is
  {"keypairs": ["keypair": {data} with an extra "keypair".
  This was a little hard to notice when functionally testing this
  earlier because when you print it out, it looks correct until
  you notice everything is in the "keypair" attribute.
* Filtering on find is broken and so a find method was added to
  manually do the filtering.
* Create needs to populate the private key in the response
  resource object.

Change-Id: Ic2fffc5a48e4270acd2711e7762cc3157a7a71df

commit_message:
policy.pp : Fix duplicate ressource issue openstacklib::policy

Currently, in the policy.pp file the class openstacklib::policy
is called. The same apply for all components resulting in a
Duplicate Ressource issue. Using directly the underlying ressource
openstacklib::policy::base we prevent this issue.

Change-Id: Ida23a774158f3275bc874d1b52a3424afeeb6fb2

subject: Disable python-barbicanclient 3.0.0 version
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2014-11-02 00:54:43.000000000', 'files': ['requirements.txt'], 'message': "Disable python-barbicanclient 3.0.0 version

python-barbicanclient 3.0.0 has introduced cliff module, but pins it
to 1.6.1, while global-requirements set it to >=1.7.0, now the whole
OpenStack projects depends on higher version of cliff, but
python-barbicanclient is needed by cinder, then grenade test will
fail because: pkg_resources.DistributionNotFound: cliff==1.6.1

As long as python-barbicanclient maintainers don't provide a patch
for 3.0.0 (which seems not happen FMPOV), we need to disbable this
version.

Change-Id: I02f055ae89989cef2bd0264c60279a1f1a141e01
Related-Bug: #1388414
(cherry picked from commit 8c477b1e3d818b8072542ba0b970ffde5b7683ca)
"}]
commit_message:
Disable python-barbicanclient 3.0.0 version

python-barbicanclient 3.0.0 has introduced cliff module, but pins it
to 1.6.1, while global-requirements set it to >=1.7.0, now the whole
OpenStack projects depends on higher version of cliff, but
python-barbicanclient is needed by cinder, then grenade test will
fail because: pkg_resources.DistributionNotFound: cliff==1.6.1

As long as python-barbicanclient maintainers don't provide a patch
for 3.0.0 (which seems not happen FMPOV), we need to disbable this
version.

Change-Id: I02f055ae89989cef2bd0264c60279a1f1a141e01
Related-Bug: #1388414
(cherry picked from commit 8c477b1e3d818b8072542ba0b970ffde5b7683ca)

commit_message:
Field "Volume name" on Horizon no longer mandatory

Change the field of "Volume name" on Horizon dashboard in process
of create or edit volume from mandatory to optional.
This is supported by the fact that Horizon dashboard displays the
volume's ID for the volume's name if its name is None or empty.

Change-Id: Ic8e6f8d3ffe51a4c2faf9ca636215e6e24f435b4
Closes-Bug: #1389172

subject: Fix concurrency issue in security-service tempest test
revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2014-10-31 06:49:33.000000000', 'files': ['contrib/tempest/tempest/api/share/test_security_services.py'], 'message': "Fix concurrency issue in security-service tempest test

Tempest test 'test_list_security_services_detailed_filter_by_ss_attributes'
is used by two modules:
  tempest.api.share.test_security_services
  tempest.api.share.admin.test_security_services.

And when both of them are running at a time, they interfere with each other.
That causes mismatch error - we expect 1 security service to be listed,
but get 2.

Remove check if length of returned list is equals to 1.

Add check if all returned security services satisfy filtering opts.

Change-Id: Ia78549209f38a8272743b1edfd2172a53ef59197
Closes-bug: #1386619
"}]
commit_message:
Fix concurrency issue in security-service tempest test

Tempest test 'test_list_security_services_detailed_filter_by_ss_attributes'
is used by two modules:
  tempest.api.share.test_security_services
  tempest.api.share.admin.test_security_services.

And when both of them are running at a time, they interfere with each other.
That causes mismatch error - we expect 1 security service to be listed,
but get 2.

Remove check if length of returned list is equals to 1.

Add check if all returned security services satisfy filtering opts.

Change-Id: Ia78549209f38a8272743b1edfd2172a53ef59197
Closes-bug: #1386619

commit_message:
Support ipxe with Dnsmasq

The workflow of ipxe in ironic now only support ISC dhcpd.
the cause is the option '!175,bootfile-name' is not recognized

commit_message:
Split up assignments, making role-assignments pluggable.

Split the current "assignments" components into the base entities
(i.e. domain, project & role) and the actual assignment model.
Make the (real) assignment part of this pluggable, so as to allow
alternative models to be introduced.

In addition, provide a base to more easily rationalize the
duplicate methods of extracting assignments.

Change-Id: I46b8298559ff6040591a9fbd02a69f99ed859af9
Implements: bp pluggable-assignment

reviewers: [{'_account_id': 3, 'name': 'Jenkins', 'username': 'jenkins'}, {'_account_id': 1179, 'name': 'Clay Gerrard', 'email': 'clay.gerrard@gmail.com', 'username': 'clay-gerrard'}, {'_account_id': 2622, 'name': 'Samuel Merritt', 'email': 'sam@swiftstack.com', 'username': 'torgomatic'}, {'_account_id': 7479, 'name': 'paul luse', 'email': 'paul.e.luse@intel.com', 'username': 'peluse'}, {'_account_id': 7485, 'name': 'Tushar Gohad', 'email': 'tushar.gohad@intel.com', 'username': 'tsg'}, {'_account_id': 8871, 'name': 'Elastic Recheck', 'username': 'elasticrecheck'}, {'_account_id': 12395, 'name': 'Roman Vasylets', 'email': 'pomeo92@gmail.com', 'username': 'rvasilets'}, {'_account_id': 13052, 'name': 'SwiftStack Cluster CI', 'email': 'openstack-ci@swiftstack.com', 'username': 'swiftstack-cluster-ci', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}]
revisions:
[{'number': 9, 'created': '2014-11-03 20:38:24.000000000', 'files': ['test/unit/proxy/test_mem_server.py', 'test/unit/proxy/test_server.py', 'swift/common/storage_policy.py', 'swift/proxy/controllers/obj.py', 'swift/proxy/controllers/base.py'], 'message': 'Foundational support for PUT of erasure-coded objects

This commit makes it possible to PUT an object into Swift and have it
stored using erasure coding instead of replication.

This works by splitting the incoming object into a number of segments,
erasure-coding each segment in turn to get fragments, then
concatenating the fragments into fragment archives. Segments are 1 MiB
in size, except the last, which is between 1 B and 1 MiB.

+====================================================================+
|                             object data                            |
+====================================================================+

                                   |
          +------------------------+----------------------+
          |                        |                      |
          v                        v                      v

+===================+    +===================+         +==============+
|     segment 1     |    |     segment 2     |   ...   |   segment N  |
+===================+    +===================+         +==============+

          |                       |
          |                       |
          v                       v

     /=========\             /=========\
     | pyeclib |             | pyeclib |         ...
     \=========/             \=========/

          |                       |
          |                       |
          +--> fragment A-1       +--> fragment A-2
          |                       |
          |                       |
          |                       |
          |                       |
          |                       |
          +--> fragment B-1       +--> fragment B-2
          |                       |
          |                       |
         ...                     ...

Then, object server A gets the concatenation of fragment A-1, A-2,
..., A-N, so its .data file looks like this (called a "fragment archive"):

+=====================================================================+
|     fragment A-1     |     fragment A-2     |  ...  |  fragment A-N |
+=====================================================================+

Since this means that the object server never sees the object data as
the client sent it, we have to do a few things to ensure data
integrity.

First, the proxy has to check the Etag if the client provided it; the
object server can't do it since the object server doesn't see the raw
data.

Second, if the client does not provide an Etag, the proxy computes it
and uses the MIME-PUT mechanism to provide it to the object servers
after the object body. Otherwise, the object would not have an Etag at
all.

Third, the proxy computes the MD5 of each fragment archive and sends
it to the object server using the MIME-PUT mechanism. With replicated
objects, the proxy checks that the Etags from all the object servers
match, and if they don't, returns a 500 to the client. This mitigates
the risk of data corruption in one of the proxy --> object connections,
and signals to the client when it happens. With EC objects, we can't
use that same mechanism, so we must send the checksum with each
fragment archive to get comparable protection.

There are a number of things _not_ included in this commit. Some of
them are listed here:

 * GET support for erasure-coded objects

 * two-step commit

 * deferred cleanup of old .data files

 * durability (daemon to reconstruct missing archives)

 * configurable segment size

Co-Authored-By: Tushar Gohad <tushar.gohad@intel.com>

Change-Id: I9c13c03616489f8eab7dcd7c5f21237ed4cb6fd2
'}]
commit_message:
Foundational support for PUT of erasure-coded objects

This commit makes it possible to PUT an object into Swift and have it
stored using erasure coding instead of replication.

This works by splitting the incoming object into a number of segments,
erasure-coding each segment in turn to get fragments, then
concatenating the fragments into fragment archives. Segments are 1 MiB
in size, except the last, which is between 1 B and 1 MiB.

+====================================================================+
|                             object data                            |
+====================================================================+

                                   |
          +------------------------+----------------------+
          |                        |                      |
          v                        v                      v

+===================+    +===================+         +==============+
|     segment 1     |    |     segment 2     |   ...   |   segment N  |
+===================+    +===================+         +==============+

          |                       |
          |                       |
          v                       v

     /=========\             /=========\
     | pyeclib |             | pyeclib |         ...
     \=========/             \=========/

          |                       |
          |                       |
          +--> fragment A-1       +--> fragment A-2
          |                       |
          |                       |
          |                       |
          |                       |
          |                       |
          +--> fragment B-1       +--> fragment B-2
          |                       |
          |                       |
         ...                     ...

Then, object server A gets the concatenation of fragment A-1, A-2,
..., A-N, so its .data file looks like this (called a "fragment archive"):

+=====================================================================+
|     fragment A-1     |     fragment A-2     |  ...  |  fragment A-N |
+=====================================================================+

Since this means that the object server never sees the object data as
the client sent it, we have to do a few things to ensure data
integrity.

First, the proxy has to check the Etag if the client provided it; the
object server can't do it since the object server doesn't see the raw
data.

Second, if the client does not provide an Etag, the proxy computes it
and uses the MIME-PUT mechanism to provide it to the object servers
after the object body. Otherwise, the object would not have an Etag at
all.

Third, the proxy computes the MD5 of each fragment archive and sends
it to the object server using the MIME-PUT mechanism. With replicated
objects, the proxy checks that the Etags from all the object servers
match, and if they don't, returns a 500 to the client. This mitigates
the risk of data corruption in one of the proxy --> object connections,
and signals to the client when it happens. With EC objects, we can't
use that same mechanism, so we must send the checksum with each
fragment archive to get comparable protection.

There are a number of things _not_ included in this commit. Some of
them are listed here:

 * GET support for erasure-coded objects

 * two-step commit

 * deferred cleanup of old .data files

 * durability (daemon to reconstruct missing archives)

 * configurable segment size

Co-Authored-By: Tushar Gohad <tushar.gohad@intel.com>

Change-Id: I9c13c03616489f8eab7dcd7c5f21237ed4cb6fd2

commit_message:
Backlog

The backlog performs two essential functions:

1.  It provides a way for a user to float an idea before committing
to a detailed analysis.  It is, instead, a way for a user to get
approval on an approach or design.

2.  It is a parking lot for specifications that are orphaned.  If a
spec is not going to be implemented by the assigned user, it will be
collected into the backlog, and be available for other developers to
implement.

Co-Authored-By: Steve Martinelli <stevemar@ca.ibm.com>
Change-Id: If546724fd535db7753a372389c3f90f3b060d9bc

commit_message:
xenapi plugins must target only Python 2.4 features

Add a comment documenting the restriction that our xenapi plugins must
target Python 2.4 features because of restrictions with the XenServer
dom0 userspace.

Change-Id: Ide130923b16c0555c3190cbd63ce97e18d18aae0
